    Captain Miller was thinking about their trip. The
insignificant amount of work that had to be performed was
easily being handled by John and Stu. When they return,
particularly if successful, they will all be hailed as astronauts.
In point of fact, they were really only oil field workers. During
the three months of their voyage, they have had almost
nothing to do. Everything about the navigation was automatic
and computer controlled. The same thing will be true of their
three and a half month return trip. During their entire nine
month voyage the only ti me they will be busy will be when they
are working the fields of Arabia-North. In fact they spent most
of the last three months reviewing some of the trickier
construction tasks that they will have to perform. That relaxed
period was over and their hard work was just about to begin.
Their computers had already begun sending telemetering
data to Earth in preparation for the final navigational
correction.
    "Hey Stu, turn on the graphics display so that we can all
see the image of the landing site," shouted John. The
computer officer obliged by punching in the appropriate
program and in seconds the half formed image appeared on
the screen.
    "As soon as the picture is completed, stored in the
computer, and processed, the final navigational correction
will be made," intoned the Captain. They were all staring
intently at the rapidly forming image. Captain Miller noted the
randomly scattered dark spots. He recalled that the original
image sent back by Voyager 29 had similar spots. Perhaps
when the picture is processed and the features enhanced he
will see the spots more clearly. He watched as the picture was
completely formed and then instantly small changes were
apparent as the image processor automatically began
working. Barely noticeable features suddenly became very
clear. Fuzzy portions were being miraculously focused. The


noise spots were eliminated. Captain Miller was enthralled by
the sparkling clear image that appeared.
    As the men continued watching the screen, they saw a
small cross in the middle of the very flat region which was the
indicated landing site. They also noticed a small circle roughly
three and a half miles to the left of the cross which was the
computers projection of where they would land if there were
no corrections. As the men stared, they saw the circle move
gradually towards the cross. They did not feel anything
because at this distance the corrections were so minute.
Within minutes the circle enclosed the cross and the
corrections ceased. This part of the flight was finished, and the
ship was right on target. All three men strapped themselves in
and waited for the landing.


    It was just moments before the landing. Captain Miller
flipped on the camera that was pointing to the landing site.
This image was digitized for the computer but merely
displayed instantly for the astronauts. They were headed dead
on towards the target. Only Captain Miller realized with shock
that he was not looking at a target marker but an impossible
feature of the terrain.
    "This is ridiculous. How did that thing get there?" cried
Miller. He could see two, or was that a third one in the corner.
But the one that they were headed straight towards demanded
his attention. It appeared to be cylindrical, less than a foot in
diameter, made of some hard shiny metal, and about twenty
feet high pointing straight out of the ground.
    "This is impossible! How could randomly placed spikes be
sticking out of an uninhabited flat planet? How could they get
there?"
    In the midst of his turmoil and shock, Captain Miller
suddenly realized that the computers would be programmed
to know that such things are impossible. The spikes would
naturally be thought of as spots of noise and removed from the
images. He and his men were about to be impailed on a spike
of noise.


