COGLAC: Taking Stock in Tommorrow's
Energy Initiative -Coal
By Annunciata E. Marino
Writer, Skyscraper Engineering
November 18, 1981


Introduction:
If you have ever thought about saving for the future by investing in
gold, real estate, or an individual retirement plan, now is the time to
join an increasing number of people from around the world who are
investing in a most revolutionary new energy source, coal.


    A relatively little publicized event, the International
Symposium  on Coal Gasification, Liquefaction and
Conversion to Electricity (COGLAC), is attracting a lot of
attention these days, perhaps as much as OPEC.
Representatives from Germany, the United Kingdom, South
Africa, Japan, Australia, and Canada, to name a few, visit
Pittsburgh annually to attend one of the most popular and
important energy symposiums in the world. The reason, coal
has reemerged one as of the most economically viable energy
resources available today. As the price of oil increases almost
daily, this valuable resource, long thought "priced out of the
ball park" due to environmental regulation, is being "pulled
from the bench".
    In 1972, students at the University of Pittsburgh
expressed a need and interest in a continuing forum in the
area of coal conversion. In response, the first COGLAC
symposium  was held in 1973. What appeared an
overwhelming response at the time, came from 75
applications postmarked from around the world. COGLAC's
members consist of the energy intensive (production)
industry, governmental agencies, those who sell processing
equipment, researchers, and others who have a vested interest
in energy production. There are also members who have
strategic and economic interest in the conference who must
have energy to sustain industry and economic growth and
development in their countries. When participants leave the
symposium, they are "up-to-the-minute" on all aspects of the
commercialization of coal conversion: the financial, technical,
environmental, etc.
     Dr. Charles S. Beroes, Professor of Chemical Engineering
 at Pitt and Chairman of COGLAC, graciously agreed to speak
 on behalf of COGLAC's efforts and to answer some questions
 (in italics) on coal conversion technology.
     Professor Beroes was born on a Pennsylvania farm that
 was situated on top of three veins of recoverable coal. As a
 child he worked in the coal mines, and by the time he began
 college, he became concerned about the nation's energy
 problems, particularly the lack of a secure energy resource.
     Beroes claims that the U.S. is the Saudia Arabia of coal.
 He says that recent projections show that we have 300 to 500
 years of coal. "The Russians have quite a bit of coal, the
 Chinese, the English and the Australians. Japan has some
 coal, too, but we have the greatest coal deposits in the world."
     What is the gasification of coal? Millions of years ago
 when coal was being formed from its original plant material,
 the vegetable matter began to coalify, that is, gases began to
 form. However, one gas, hydrogen, was removed in this
 process. Today, gasification means adding the hydrogen
 produced from steam, to the gases produced by the burning of
 coal.
     The actualization of this process, however, is not a simple


matter. Burning coal produces toxic gases (SO2) that destroy
the function of alveoli in our lungs. Sulpher removal is of
tremendous importance to protect our lungs. Each person is
born with approximately 6 million alveoli, much more than we
need. Nevertheless, we want to preserve them so that we're
healthy when we get older. If we reduce the lungs ability to
take in oxygen, we put a greater strain on the heart and the
body will fail somewhere else.
     Describe some of the important processes that have
recently been developed in this area? One of the problems
with the gasification of coal is the lack of a simple proven
process. Over the years, roughly ten processes have been
developed and researched. But, there has been no existing
commercial operation utilizing any gasification technique that
serves as a prototype.
    However, there have been exciting developments in the
processed removal of sulpher and toxic gases from that gas
produced from coal. It is called Flue Gas Desulfurization
(FGD). Presently, there are about 140to 160 designs available.
The largest model ever built is the Bruce-Mansfield operation
located in Shippingport, Pennsylvania. It uses over 2500 tons
of coal per day and generates over 2,000 megawatts of
electricity per day.
    The costliest item on the list of coal expenditures is
transportation. As much as 25% of the coal is lost through the
combintation of transport, refining, and industrial use.
    Is the idea of slurrying coal a response to this expense?
 Recent technology is looking into the possibility of slurrying
 the coal. Through the use of water, as much as one part water
 to one part coal, the transportation costs are minimal
 compared to other methods, ie., rail, barge, ocean liner. One
 disadvantage is that now you have a great amount of water
 that would need to be removed from the coal. But, this is a
 technological challenge. In fact, the whole energy scene is full
 of technological challenges, one on top of the other.
     Describe the in-situ process. The in-situ method of
 producing gas from coal is another of these challenges. This
 process involves drilling into the coal bed, producing
 fractures with explosives, then pumping air in controlled
 amounts through one pipe while collecting the gas produced
 through another pipe. However, the hydrogen-carbon ratio
 (BTU value) is much greater through the previously
 mentioned refining of coal (FGD) than the present method of
 in-situ processing.
     Would the production of synfuels from coal affect the
 amount of C02 presently being released into the atmosphere?
 Anytime a fossil fuel is being burned, it will release CO2.
 Furthermore, from careful measurement on various places on
 the earth, it has been determined that an increasing amount of
 CO2 has been released into the atmosphere. But, as long as we
 have the oceans, they will continue to remove CO2, and this




question really addresses the issue of energy demand versus
energy supply.
    In addition to the removal of certain toxic substances in
coal, as well as the removal of CO2, another exciting
conversion process is the production of methanol from coal
for use in automobiles. The combusion engine, after minor
adjustments are made, can operate on methanol. the
production of ethanol from grain is not as feasible as the
production of methanol. If we plant every arable acre in the
U.S., we could not produce enough grain to run our
automobiles. In a recent competition, a sizeable amount of
money was offered to the maker of an automobile that uses an
alternative fuel.
    What were the results? It was found that an automobile
can be made to run on just about anything, for example, sewer
gas or wood.
    If the U. S. increased its production of coal, do you see the
likelihood of an increased exportation of coal to be in conflict
with the national goal of a secure source of energy? Coal
exports have increased in the past and will continue to
increase. Because coal is much cheaper than oil, coal will
replace oil. An increase in the use and export of coal will
contribute to the continuation of this nation's standard of
living.
    Professor Beroes has been dating major oil finds on a wall
map of the world that he keeps in his office.He tells me that
there have been no major oil finds of any commercial value for
the past five years, and that coal conversion processes provide
an optimistic energy future. "At present this country produces
only about 45% of the total amount of oil it needs and imports
oil at a cost over $94 billion per year. So the future of coal
refining is just as great as ever. Burning oil in a power plant at
$35 per barrel is equivalent to $5.38 per million BTU. Burning


coal in the same power plant at $13.89 per ton is equivalent to
$2.12 per million BTU. The bottom line is simple economics,
burning oil is two and one half times as much as coal."
    Beroes predicts that the mining and purifying of coal will
produce more jobs than any industry we now have. "The
production of clean fuels from coal will be one of the major
industries in this country and in the world. Presently, this
country is not in a negotiating position because we must have
foreign oil," he continues, "a push toward the use of coal will
give us a strong negotiating position."
    In addition to the environmental, social and political
aspects of coal conversion, a wide range of technological
advances and "challenges" are covered at the COGLAC
symposium. In order to educate the novice in this fast growing
field, a basic course on coal gasification, liquefaction and
refining has been developed. This course was offered by Pitt
last August and was conducted by Charles S. Beroes and Alan
J. Brainard, Professor of Chemical Engineering, and James T.
Cobb, Professor of Chemical Engineering and Director of the
Master of Energy Resources Program.
    The next COGLAC Symposium is scheduled for August
3-5, 1982. Papers presented at the symposium are by invitation
only; however, registration is open to all interested persons.
    The scope of COGLAC covers a wide range of
opportunities available to resolve the complex energy
problem facing the world today. Maximization of these
opportunities is encouraging global cooperation and
development, particularly by those countries who presently
consume more oil than they produce. But, it has been the
association between energy use and the GNP that has
enlightened the energy consciousness of the world and has
created the rising interest in the economic potentiality of coal
conversion processes.


