    Maybe it won't be so bad, muttered Burk. After all, I am in
on what may be the biggest story of all time. perhaps his
mounting enthusiasm was just a consequence of all the
impressive electronic monitoring equipment and the nervous
chatter of the technicians. Houston control is an exciting
place to be just before an extraterrestrial landing, let alone this
one. His job was only to interview the project director,
whomever elese he could talk to and then write the story for
The Sentinel. Interviewing engineers with all their inevitable
technical jargon could be very tedious indeed. He must pay
attention if he expected to get the facts of the story straight.
    Burk need hardly be reminded that the purpose of this
flight was oil. It seemed that everything one did these days was
dictated by the need to conserve every drop of it. Didn't he
have to take the commuter two hours early because there
wasn't enough fuel for more than two runs a day? He
remembered vividly being packed in like a sardine in near
darkness. At least they let him wander around and observe the
excitement while waiting to see Dr. Sanders. He marveled at
the relative coolness of the air inside Houston Control.
Evidently, its vast array of solar cells supplies sufficient energy


that a small amount of air conditioning was possible. What
luxury! It has been years since Burk experienced the pleasure
of cooled air.
    The fuel shortage was so acute that extraterrestrial
exploration, even for fuel itself, was thought to be out of the
question. No one could justify burning thousands of gallons of
fuel for any reason, no matter how important. In fact, Burk
remembered all of the bitter arguments when two years ago,
Voyager 29, a small unmanned spaceship and the last one
before this one, was sent out to examine the newly discovered
moon of Jupitor. Even though the scientists were sure that this
moon was loaded with oil, burning fuel for space exploration
was nearly impossible then and totally impossible now. And
yet, Captain Miller and his crew were out there, thanks to all
that was learned from Voyager 29.
    Voyager 29 proved conclusively that Arabia-North, as it
became known, contains veritable oceans of oil just below its
surface. Even so, no further exploration was permitted until
Dr. Sanders proposed Operation Tanker. He argued that it was
possible to send out an oil burning ship this fall, when the
relative locations of Earth and Jupitor were favorable, and


