    "Good to see you, Mr. Burkowski", bellowed Dr. Sander's
as he pumped Burk's hand. "What do you want to talk about?"
    "First I want to make sure that I fully understand the
technical aspects of this flight. For one thing, was the design
of the prefabricated oil refinery the trickiest engineering
problem?"
    "It was certainly one of the hardest problems", answered
Dr. Sanders. "As you may know, there are two crucial
constraints. In the first place, Captain Miller and his crew have
only two and a half months to complete the entire task of
drilling, constructing the refinery, and refining the oil. If it
takes longer, the positions of Jupitor and Earth become
rapidly unfavorable and the ship may not be able to return to
Earth for years. They use up every drop of fuel when they land
and cannot return unless they are able to find and refine the
oil; so the two and a half time constraint is crucial. The other
constraint is a problem for all aspects of this flight and that is
weight efficiency. The lighter the refinery, even though it
remains on Arabia-North, the less fuel we need for take-off
and landing."
    "In fact, the most complex aspect of the flight was the
need to husband every last drop of fuel, to save every last
ounce of weight, to add small efficiencies to every part of the
ship. There were many ingenius fuel savings, and without any
one of them, this flight would not have had a chance to break
even or with luck bring back a little extra fuel."
    "Could you give me an example of one of these novel fuel
savings, Dr. Sanders?"
    "Of course! You can see one of them by just looking at the
image on that screen of the landing site." All that Burk could
see was a scene of desolation and a total absence of plant life.
"If you were a trained geol, Mr. Burkowski, that scene would
shout 'oil', but that is not the aspect I want you to examine. For
an area of 20 square miles surrounding the landing site, the
ground is almost completely flat and level. Our cameras can
observe the details down to less than a foot, even though this
picture was taken at an altitude of 50,000feet. The landing site
is as flat as it looks in the picture. When we saw that image, we
realized that we could simplify the landing procedure. If the
ship is coming down in the middle of that area, there is no need
for horizontal corrections. The on-board computer need only
use fuel, with perfect efficiency to slow the ship down.
Eliminating any reserve fuel that would be necessary for
horizontal correction was the saving that put over the top. We
will repeat the saving on the return flight landing on the
Nevada salt flats."
