     Burk was suitably impressed with the fact that they were
 saving as much fuel as possible. He was also impressed with
 the remarkable quality of the image of the landing site. "I know
 about the quality of your cameras, but how could you transmit
 so faithfully over such a long distance? I understand the power
 of your transmitters was only around 10 watts.
     "That's a good question", responded Sanders with only a
 touch of condescention. "Since the beginning of space
 exploration, images have been transmitted via discrete
 communication techniques. The image is first discretized by
 sampling it 40,000 times and then quantizing each a sample
 into 64 levels. This discrete image is then divided into 240,000
 binary pulses. These pulses are transmitted slowly to Earth,
 taking a few hours for the entire image, where a receiver picks
 out the long, if very weak, pulses from the noise and decides if
 they are positive or negative. The code is then reformed into
 the image. Of course the receiver still makes a number of
 mistakes. To cut these errors way down, additional pulses are
 added which enable our ground computers to correct many of
 these errors. In spite of this, a few errors are still made.
 Actually our biggest problem is not the errors made during
 transmission but various kinds of noise at the source. The
 principle source of this noise is the distortion caused by the
 weak atmosphere of the moon and interfering dust-like
 particles."
    "Here, let me show you what I'm talking about Mr.
Burkowski. The original image of the landing site is still in our
computers." Saying this, Dr. Sanders moved quickly to one of
the terminals and pushed a number of buttons. Buck saw the
image appearing on the screen. It looked very similar to the
image he had seen previously but with some differences. This
image was not as clear as the final version.
    "You may notice many differences Mr. Burkowski. For
one thing, there is a weak snow-like noise over part of the
original image. This noise is caused by the transmission errors
that our decoders could not correct. Some parts of this
picture, particularly here in the lower left corner, are fuzzy.
This was caused by atmoshperic conditions. There is another
form of noise that appears as randomly scattered dark spots.
We presume that these are dust particles. Whether they were
actually on the camera's lens or are some sort of dust cloud, is
very hard to tell. Inspite of these noises, the terrain is clearly
visible and your eye can separate the image from the noise."
    "That's very interesting, Dr. Sanders, but how were these
distortions removed from the picture?"
    "Oh, that is done by image processing techniques. The
basic idea of these procedures was developed in the seventies.
Since then we have refined things to the point where we can
remove the noise without affecting the image in the slightest.
Actually our image processing not only removes the noise, but
it enhances certain kinds of terrain features. Observe this
rather faint line in the original picture. In the processed picture
we clearly see that this line is in reality the edge of a nine foot
drop. Such a drop would be very dangerous in the landing
zone, but as you can see it is eight miles from the targeted
landing spot. So you see our image processing techniques are
responsible for the high quality of our image."
    "Excuse me for a little while Mr. Burkowski, but the ship is
nearing its last navigational correction point and the tele
metering has started to come in. I want to make sure that
everything is okay."
    "Sure Dr. Sanders, I'll just stay out of the way and watch."
